      "title": "Velocity of Efflux",
      "conceptBody": "<h3>Velocity of Efflux</h3><p><img src=\"data:image/jpeg;base64,\" width=\"212\" height=\"176\">&nbsp;</p><p>Suppose that a liquid is taken in a container of large cross sectional area ${{A}_{1}}$. There is also a small hole of cross-sectional area ${{A}_{2}}$ on the wall of the container. Suppose that the velocity of efflux of the liquid out of the container is ${{\\text{v}}_{2}}$. The velocity of a liquid particle at the surface at that instant is ${{\\text{v}}_{1}}$. The height of the liquid column at any instant from the position of the hole to the upper end of the tank is $\\text{h}$, and the atmospheric pressure is ${{\\text{P}}_{0}}$ Now from the principle of continuity, we get</p><p>${{\\text{v}}_{1}}\\text{ }\\!\\!~\\!\\!\\text{ }{{\\text{A}}_{1}}={{\\text{v}}_{2}}\\text{ }\\!\\!~\\!\\!\\text{ }{{\\text{A}}_{2}}$ … (1)</p><p>Applying Bernoulli's principle at the free end outside the hole and also at the surface, we get</p><p>${{\\text{P}}_{0}}+\\frac{1}{2}\\rho \\text{v}_{1}^{2}+\\rho gh={{\\text{P}}_{0}}+\\frac{1}{2}\\rho \\text{v}_{2}^{2}$ … (2)</p><p>Therefore, from equations (1) and (2), we get,</p><p>$\\text{v}_{2}^{2}=\\frac{2\\text{gh}}{\\left[ 1-{{\\left( \\frac{{{\\text{A}}_{2}}}{\\text{ }\\!\\!~\\!\\!\\text{ }{{\\text{A}}_{1}}} \\right)}^{2}} \\right]}$ … (3)</p><p>If ${{\\text{A}}_{2}}\\ll {{\\text{A}}_{1}}$ then,</p><p>${{\\text{v}}_{2}}=\\sqrt{2\\text{gh}}$ … (4)</p><p>Equation (3) and (4) give the velocity of efflux of a liquid coming out in a small hole in a tank.</p><p><strong>Important note&nbsp;</strong></p><p>(i) $\\text{ }\\!\\!~\\!\\!\\text{ v}\\propto \\sqrt{\\text{h}}$</p><p>(ii) $\\text{v}$ is independent of nature of liquid.</p><p>(iii) If the liquid is ejected through the hole horizontally and the hole is at a height $\\text{h}$ from the upper level of liquid and the total depth of liquid is $\\text{H}$, then the time taken by the liquid to reach the ground is :</p><p>$\\text{t}=\\sqrt{\\frac{2\\left( \\text{H}-\\text{h} \\right)}{\\text{g}}}$ … (5)</p><p>Suppose that horizontal distance travelled by the liquid stream is $\\text{x}$, i.e. the liquid will strikes the ground at a distance $\\text{x}$ from the base of the container below the hole.</p><p>Then, $\\text{ }\\!\\!~\\!\\!\\text{ }x=v.t=\\sqrt{2\\text{gh}}\\cdot \\sqrt{\\frac{2\\left( \\text{H}-\\text{h} \\right)}{\\text{g}}}$ … (6)</p><p>This range $\\text{x}$ will be maximum if $\\frac{\\text{dx}}{\\text{dh}}=0$</p><p>$\\text{ }\\!\\!~\\!\\!\\text{ }$ Now, $\\text{ }\\!\\!~\\!\\!\\text{ }{{x}^{2}}=4h\\left( H-h \\right)$. Therefore, $2x\\frac{dx}{dh}=4H-8h=0$</p><p>Therefore, $\\text{ }\\!\\!~\\!\\!\\text{ H}=2\\text{ }\\!\\!~\\!\\!\\text{ h}$ i.e. $\\text{h}=\\text{H}/2$ … (7)</p><p>And ${{\\text{x}}_{\\text{max}}}=2\\sqrt{\\frac{\\text{H}}{2}\\left( \\text{H}-\\text{H}/2 \\right)}\\text{ }\\!\\!~\\!\\!\\text{ i}\\text{.e}\\text{. }\\!\\!~\\!\\!\\text{ }{{\\text{X}}_{\\text{max}}}=\\text{H}$ … (8)</p>",
      "position": 0,
      "qcConcept": "66a0db7bc03b9dcaf1afe202"
    }
